What is a key difference between these materials?

Concrete and steel are man-made materials. Soils are natural materials. Therefore, We must investigate and characterize them first!

Site investigation

Objectives
  • Stratigraphy
  • Soil properties
  • Establish groundwater conditions
  • Hazards
Purpose
  • Assess the site's suitability.
  • Assess existing geohazards in the site.
  • Achieve cost-effective, resilient, and safe design.
  • Identify issues that may arise during execution.

Desk study

Purpose: Find information on the following:
  • Probable ground conditions (e.g., topography, soil and rock type, groundwater table)
  • Previous land-use
  • Access to the site
Why do desk studies?

Cheaper to obtain than to generate new data.

Information typically available:
  • Geological maps
  • Aerial photographs
  • Topographic maps
  • Previous site investigation reports

Case history 3.1: The Oso Landslide

Draw conclusions on the suitability of land development in the zone marked in red. What is important to look at in this aerial image?
  • Precedent is important: Comparing aerial images in time, tells you history of the site. Visible scars, bumpy terrain, and visible deformations over time indicate instability
  • Always check the water: Water erodes and deposits materials, but also infiltrates in porous media reducing its strength. Understanding how water moves in a site is key
  • High value, zero cost: Many geohazards can be identified from aerial images at global scales. Never skip the view from above

Walk-over surveys

The purpose is to check and make additions to the information already collected during the desk study.
Should include:
  1. Inspection of the site and surrounding area on foot
  2. Examination of the local records not included in the desk study
  3. Surveying local residents about the site

Features that should be identified:

  1. Slopes angles
  2. Exposures
  3. Vegetation
  4. Instabilities (scarps, tension cracks)
  5. Water conditions (surface and subsurface)
  6. Structures
  7. Access

Subsurface exploration

The purpose is to determine:
  1. Soil types
  2. Soil strength
  3. Depth to bedrock
  4. Rock type and quality
  5. Groundwater levels
Three components of exploration:
  1. Boring or excavation
  2. Sampling
  3. Testing:
    1. Laboratory testing
    2. In-situ testing

Boring

Purpose:
  1. Obtain samples of geologic materials for classification and laboratory testing
  2. Enable in-situ measurements of the physical and engineering properties of soil
How many boreholes and what layout should I use for a project?

  1. Number, type, location, and depth of investigation depend on:
    1. Nature and size of project
    2. Variation of soil conditions
    3. Budget for site investigation
    4. Spacing depends on the spatial variability of soil conditions and type of structures
    5. Depth of investigation depends on extend to which the soil is affected by external loads/factors

Sampling methods

Soil samples are collected at various depths during drilling for further analysis. Depending on objective, two types of samples can be recovered:

  1. Disturbed samples: Used for soil classification and index properties. Obtained when soil structure is altered during sampling.
  2. Intact ("undisturbed") samples: Used for determining engineering properties. Obtained when soil structure is preserved during sampling.

Shelby tubes

  • Thin-walled, hollow steel tubes for geotechnical investigation
  • Typically used in soft to medium silts and clays
  • Pushed into the ground, not driven, to minimize disturbance
  • Use to determine engineering properties in the lab (e.g., strength, compressibility)

In-situ testing

In-situ tests are used to obtain information on the characteristics of soil, when intact sampling is not feasible (e.g., for coarse-grained soils)

Most popular devices are:

  1. Standard Penetration Test (SPT)
  2. Cone Penetrometer Test (CPT)
  3. Vane Shear Test (VST)
  4. Pressuremeter Test (PMT)
  5. Flat Plate Dilatometer Test (DMT)

Standard Penetration test (SPT)

This tests determines a penetration resistance value \(N\) which can be used to obtain various soil properties.
is defined as the number of blows required to drive a standard sampler 300 mm (12 in) into the soil using a 63.5 kg (140 lb) hammer falling a distance of 760 mm (30 in). The sampler is driven in three increments of 150 mm (6 in) each, and the sum of the number of blows for the last two increments is recorded as the \(N\) value.
\( N= N_f + N_s \)
Notes on the use of SPT in the field
  • When the \(N \geq 50\) for a penetration of less or equal to 150 mm (6 in), the test should be stopped and the value recorded as \(N = 50+\). This is called a refusal
  • The number of blows during the seating stage is not recorded because of soil disturbance effects due to drilling down do desired depth and loss of confinement due to excavation
  • Hammering efficiency and flexibility of the system will affect energy delivery to the soil, thereby affecting the \(N\) value
  • The SPT test is typically used for coarse-grained soils, where intact sampling is unfeasible

Split barrel sampler

It is used during SPT field investigation to recover disturbed soil samples.

  1. Samples are typically used to measure index properties like moisture content, gradation, Atterberg Limits, visual classification
  2. Not used for: strength or consolidation testing

SPT Hammer types

Three types of hammer available. Each one has a unique efficiency
Ratio of energy delivered by hammer blow to the theoretical potential energy of the hammer.
\( E_E= E_h / E_{max} \)
\(E_{max}= 4200 \) lb-in
Hammer type Efficiency \(E_E\)
Donut 0.45
Safety 0.60
Automatic 0.78
\(N\)-value must be corrected to a energy level of 60% efficiency
\( N_{60} = N \times C_E \times C_B \times C_S \times C_R \)


\(C_E=\) Energy correction factor
\(C_B=\) Borehole diameter correction factor
\(C_S=\) Sampler correction factor
\(C_R=\) Rod length correction factor


Hammer Correction factor
Donut 0.75
Safety 1.0
Automatic 1.3

Example 3.1

For the data attached, calculate \(N\) and \(N_{60}\). The automatic hammer was used.

Step 1: calculate \(N\)
\( N= N_f + N_s = 7 + 11 = \color{green} 18 \) blows/ft

Step 2: calculate \(N_{60}\)
\( \begin{align} N_{60} & = N \times C_E \times C_B \times C_S \times C_R \\ &= 18 \times 1.3 \times 1.0 \times 1.0 \times 1.0 \\ N_{60} & = \color{green} 23 \text{ blows/ft} \end{align} \)

For sand:
  • Relative density \(D_r\)
  • Friction angle \(\phi\)
  • Elastic modulus \(E_s\)
  • Liquefaction potential

For clay:
  • Undrained shear strength \(S_u\)
  • Stress history
  • Lateral stress ratio \(K_o\)
  • Undrained elastic modulus \(E_u\)

SPT - Strengths and Limitations

Strengths

  • Obtain sample and \(N\)
  • Simple and rugged device \(\implies\) low cost
  • Suitable for many soil types
  • Can perform in weak rocks
  • Available throughout the USA and worldwide

Limitations

  • Obtain results at discrete depths
  • Disturbed samples only
  • Crude number for analysis
  • Not reliable for soft clays and silts
  • High variability and uncertainty

Cone penetration test

The CPT is a push-in test that measures the resistance of the soil to a conical tip penetrating it.
  • The cone is advanced at constant rate of 2 cm/s.
  • Tip \(q_c\) and sleeve friction \(f_s\) resistance are measured.
  • Pore water pressure \(u_2\) is measured.
  • Measures are near-continuous.

Cone dimensions and definitions

A variety of cone configurations are possible. Below is a list of most common dimensions for cone penetrometers.
  • Cone apex angle \(\alpha\) 60 degrees .
  • Cone diameter: 37.5 mm for \(A_c=10 \text{cm}^2\).
    \(D=43.7\) mm for \(A_c=15 \text{cm}^2\).
  • Friction sleeve area: \(A_s= 150 \text{cm}^2\) for \(A_c=10 \text{cm}^2\) and \(A_s= 225 \text{cm}^2\) for \(A_c=15 \text{cm}^2\).
  • Common location for pore filter in CPTu is \(u_2\).
Other sensors can be mounted in the cone to measure additional parameters.
What is used to create reaction and advance the cone?
CPT measurements can be use for soil profiling

CPT- Strengths and limitations

Strengths

  • Obtain continuous profile of soil properties
  • Repeatable reliable data (not operator dependent)
  • Economical and rapid
  • Strong theoretical basis for interpretation

Limitations

  • Requires specialized equipment and trained personnel
  • Difficult in gravelly soils
  • No soil sample recovery

Geophysical methods

Use of physical principles to investigate subsurface conditions. Common methods include:
  • Seismic surveys (measuring wave propagation)
  • Electric surveys (measure soil's electric resistivity)
Te combination of boreholes, SPT and CPT data, and Geophysics produces the most accurate profile interpretation
